        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-03-24T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-03-24T12:00:00-05:00" n="178" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d178">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 PW/3–2445: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-03-24T18:00:00+01:00">March 24, 1945—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received March 25—2:18 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1425. For Acting Secretary and Assistant Secretary Dunn. When I took Judge
                        Rosenman<note n="18" xml:id="d178fn1">Samuel I. Rosenman, Special Counsel to
                        President Roosevelt on mission in Europe.</note> to call on General de
                    Gaulle this afternoon, General de Gaulle said to me as we were leaving: “It
                    seems clear now that your Government does not want to help our troops in
                    Indo-China. Nothing has yet been dropped to them by parachute.” I spoke of
                    distances and he said “No, that is not the question; the question is one of
                    policy I assume.”</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
